Notation idea for game theory.
- It's convenient to use notation u_i(a_i, a_{-i}) for the profile with i using a_i and others using a_{-i}. 
- It's convenient to order players and let a=(a_1,...,a_n).
- These conventions can conflict: e.g. in a symmetric game, which payoff is u_2(x,y) talking about?

So I think we should start using u_i(a_i | a_{-i}) for the first one. Then, in my example: 
- Payoff u_2(x,y) will mean 1 uses x and 2 uses y.
- Payoff u_2(x|y) will mean 1 uses y and 2 uses x.

You know, we don't talk about the fact that Yoo Joonghyuk actually has another Kim Dokja reason to hate his other selves, and this one is more grounded. I think the pieces get put together in a frustrating way when Yoo Joonghyuk learns that Kim Dokja knows about his future regressions and such+

and that Kim Dokja's schemes are based off of them. That means the bullshit Kim Dokja does was heavily influenced by future Yoo Joonghyuks.
Something we don't remember is that 3rd turn Yoo Joonghyuk is "still human". He's empathetic, and he does genuinely care about people and humanity and his team+

Which means he can see for himself through Kim Dokja how his future selves became a mess. He can put together the pieces of what Kim Dokja meant in his conversation with Yoo Joonghyuk on the rooftop. We know this, because this scene was critical for Yoo Joonghyuk's character arc. It's not just about

not regressing, but the fact that Kim Dokja's wish is for Yoo Joonghyuk to maintain that humanity.
So Yoo Joonghyuk's anger at his future selves teaching Kim Dokja that the way forward was to continually hurt his companions for the sake of the "greater good" would dig a lot more at this still human+

(read: empathetic and not broken yet) Yoo Joonghyuk who values his companions as more than just a means to the end.
Every Yoo Joonghyuk is arrogant. It's a core character trait for them. So Yoo Joonghyuk, who is aware of just how many failures lay ahead of him, would of course be pissy with his

future selves for not only causing harm to them all, but teaching Kim Dokja the bullshit that he does.

It's not their fault anymore than Yoo Joonghyuk's himself, but the point still stands. It's on sight.

chased or surrounded, but are holding the positions they took after leaving the Sudzha district.
Belgorod region: The heavily mobilized Ukrainian troops have been playing â€œcat and mouseâ€ near the borders for several days.

The Ukrainian armed forces attacked and severely damaged the bridge in Grafivka. There is fighting in the area around Demydivka, where the southern and central part of the settlement is in the gray zone: Russian troops only maintain control

over part of the settlement. Heavy fighting is underway for Demidivka and in the area of forest plantations adjacent to the settlement. Russian troops move some of their forces from the Kursk region. In a joint operation with the Ukrainian Main Intelligence Service, missile

forces and artillery, the special operations forces destroyed 2 Mi-8 helicopters and 2 Ka-52 helicopters at a position far behind the Russian defense lines without casualties.
Russian soldiers looted houses in the village of Repyakhovka in the Belgorod region. 2 women were killed after

their car was attacked by drones in the Belgorod region.
Northern sector: Increased Russian pressure is reported in the Vovchansk district. Having had little success at the bridgehead along the Oskil River, Russian troops are trying further south,

along the Novomlynsk-Dvorichna-Zapadne line, where the Russians have become more active in the area around Topoliv, Krasny Pershy, and now also north of Kamyanka, where they are creating a new bridgehead. The area is held by units from the mobile border division,

which are not particularly well suited to holding the coast and need to be reinforced.
Eastern sector: Russian troops continue attacks in the Pokrovsk district, but lose important positions in the previously occupied villages. Ukrainian air scout directed aircraft to the Russian command post:

A group of Russian troops consisting of several brigades was hit and effectively slowed down in the Toretsk area. The town of Donetskoye was hit by Russian artillery: an apartment building was damaged and a local resident was killed.

Southern sector: A Russian combined company providing security for the crossing was wiped out by precision artillery attacks in Dnipryany in the occupied

part of Kherson The situation on the Pyatikhatki-Stepeve-Maly Shcherbaky line remains tense: the Russians are constantly trying to pressure the Ukrainians. Attacks are carried out by small infantry groups, sometimes even one person at a time, as well as using motorcycles,

For classical liberals liberalism was a struggle between individuals and the state; between their rights and its power.

This aligns well with early democratic systems as the state (presently or in a not far too distant past) often had diverging interests of the ones found in its population

But nowadays the struggle of individuals rights is not between the state and its people, but found between its population itself.

This is due to two things. The first being that the majority now has a far greater knowledge of sociology and all the ramifications of socioeconomic disparities and

two, as society has moved towards a more progressive interpretation of liberal values the state has moved from being in opposition to its citizen rights to being its defender against illiberal forces. Particularly at home where a minority has gained traction in wanting to go back to a fetishize past

This is in my opinion the main difference of modern liberalism and classical liberalism.

Humans rights are being reinterpreted because their rational interpretation based on facts leads to a more egalitarian society where capitalism must be constrained (or eliminated) among other things.

But this is not to say that defending human rights from the state is unnecessary. This struggle still exist and as illiberal forces take power the struggle is more and more present. But it is in my opinion not the main struggle anymore.

This doesn't make any sense to me, though. SOMEBODY is going to own Berkshire Hathaway shares. Whether it is owned by one person or a million people doesn't change the value in the shares.

Warren Buffett could sell all of his shares, collecting money from other investors, and then donate it to charity. Or, he could keep the money, and those other investors could donate it to charity (or spend it, or whatever) instead of buying BRK.A shares. There's no functional difference.

Buffett's argument is that he is a uniquely gifted investor, and will be able to more efficiently direct Berkshire's investments in other companies than the collection of a million shareholders he'd be able to sell BRK.A shares to would be able to. 

Given his history, that seems plausible.
Any arguments about whether or not billionaires should be taxed more is irrelevant to whether Buffett should voluntarily sell his shares now or do it later.

On 30 April 1977 a dozen mothers walked to the Plaza de Mayo in Argentina's capital city wearing white handkerchiefs to find the desaparecidos.

Initially, the lack of media coverage of the disappearances led the mothers to believe that they were alone in their plight.

During the late 1970s, tens of thousands of men, women and even children were abducted by the right-wing military government in Argentina.

A small group of mothers of the disappeared began staging weekly demonstrations to demand that their children be released & the kidnappers be brought to justice

Las Madres(The Mothers) & Las Abuelas(Grandmothers) of Plaza de Mayo were formed to find the children stolen and illegally adopted during the 1976â€“83 Argentine military dictatorship.

In 2005 DNA analysis of human remains from mass graves identified many of the disappeared.

I'm skeptical of arguments that certain behaviours emerge automatically from the right combination of inputs. So, I don't think it's likely that having emotion gives us behavioural flexibility, unless we design a system to regulate behaviour under competing affective signals trying to drive it.

So then we're talking about a behaviour regulator, and the question is: does that buy us anything vis Ã  vis the property of intelligence? Does multimodality of affect requiring regulation buy us anything? Under the definition I gave earlier, it doesn't seem to.

Figuring out how to satisfy an arbitrary goal for a given interpretation (whether embedded in an agent or not) is a form of search, using a world-model and predictions about the effects of possible interventions. So long as we're minimally informed about the goal, that's possible.

But, finding good interpretations, ensuring that interventions are normative, this seems to be a place where we want competing drives and we want to use them to regulate behaviour, particularly in the latter case. We don't want AI to be singlemindedly goal-directed.

So my statement here is that we can reasonably define general intelligence for the singleminded goal-directed format, but if we want AI to have social intelligence, emotion, if perhaps not strictly necessary, seems like it would be useful. And social intelligence is a good property to have.
